<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="23" type="distribution">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="23">Distribution.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="23">
North, Central, and South America (
<bibRefCitation pageId="0" pageNumber="23">Brako 1991</bibRefCitation>
), Africa (
<bibRefCitation author="Timdal, E" journalOrPublisher="Mycotaxon" pageId="0" pageNumber="23" pagination="57 - 90" title="Further studies on African species of the lichen genus Phyllopsora (Lecanorales)." volume="77" year="2001">Timdal and Krog 2001</bibRefCitation>
), Asia.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="23" type="remarks">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="23">Remarks.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="23">
The species (Fig. 6C) was reported from India by 
<bibRefCitation author="Mishra, GK" journalOrPublisher="Mycotaxon" pageId="0" pageNumber="23" pagination="29 - 44" title="New taxa and new reports of Phyllopsora (lichenized Ascomycotina) from India." url="https://doi.org/10.5248/115.29" volume="115" year="2011">Mishra et al (2011)</bibRefCitation>
, and we confirm its presence in Asia by DNA sequences (mtSSU and ITS; 456) from material from Thailand. The species is sister to a clade comprising 
<taxonomicName genus="P." lsidName="P. byssiseda" pageId="0" pageNumber="23" rank="species" species="byssiseda">P. byssiseda</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName genus="P." lsidName="P. fendleri" pageId="0" pageNumber="23" rank="species" species="fendleri">P. fendleri</taxonomicName>
(Fig. 1). It is new to Thailand.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
